# Prior work

List of related papers with one-paragraph summaries. Collected at the start of a new
project (5-10 papers) and extended whenever a new hypothesis is added.

## Format

```markdown
## [Author (Year)] Title

- **venue**: [journal / conference / arxiv id]
- **citations**: [Google Scholar / Semantic Scholar count]
- **URL / DOI**: [link]
- **main claim**: [one or two sentences]
- **method**:
  - model type: [math / classical ML / deep learning / RL / foundation model]
  - data: [universe, period, frequency]
  - validation: [split, k-fold, walk-forward, ...]
- **results**:
  - main metric: [Sharpe X, PSR Y, etc.]
- **limitations** (stated by the authors, or evident weaknesses):
  - ...
- **relation to this research**: [use / compare / differentiate from / refute]
```

## Example

```markdown
## Avellaneda & Lee (2010) Statistical arbitrage in the U.S. equities market

- **venue**: Quantitative Finance 10(7): 761-782
- **citations**: 2000+
- **URL**: https://doi.org/10.1080/14697680903124632
- **main claim**:
  Models the residual returns of U.S. equities after factor decomposition as an
  Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process; uses an s-score to generate signals for a market-neutral
  strategy. Compares PCA decomposition with sector-ETF decomposition.
- **method**:
  - model type: math (OU process, AR(1) regression, PCA)
  - data: U.S. equities (market cap > $1B), 1996-2007, daily EOD
  - validation: time-ordered split (2000-2002 used as the training period for s-score
    thresholds)
- **results**:
  - PCA Sharpe: 1.44 (1997-2007)
  - ETF Sharpe: 1.10 (1997-2007); volume-aware variant: 1.51 (2003-2007)
- **limitations**:
  - performance degrades after 2003
  - large drawdown during the August 2007 liquidity crisis
  - more sophisticated portfolio strategies left as future work
  - single asset class (U.S. equities only)
- **relation to this research**:
  Comparison reference. The differentiation is in the asset class and timeframe.
```

## Search strategy

- arxiv.org (q-fin.* categories)
- SSRN (working papers and recent activity)
- Google Scholar — sort by citation count on the topic's base terms
- Snowball back from recent papers' references to canonical works

## When to update

Whenever a new hypothesis is added, revisit this file and add new papers if needed.
